<id>http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=6218&amp;p=27211#p27211</id>
<link href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=6218&amp;p=27211#p27211"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Windows 10 Style? (Even with &quot;dead&quot; tiles? .-. )]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=6218&amp;p=27211#p27211"><![CDATA[
Tiles are a decent way to store lots of links in a small uniform space... Unlike Icons they create a sense of uniformity and organization because they are all the same shape.. which is aesthetically pleasing.. This combined with the minimization of background space of squares give tiles a unique and 'professional' feel when compared to if they were all round.. They are however only useful once you are familiar with the current layout because its harder to remember an icon than a name... (though its easier to spot a remembered icon, than a remembered name)<br />The purpose of 2x1 and 2x2 and 4x1 tiles is mostly for dividing them up for easier recall.<br />I have android, Iphone, and windows phones, and I Prefer windows phone above the others; with exception to the low quantity of apps available... (If they could allow android apps to run native on windows phone, that would be amazing) because In my opinion its just easier to find what your looking for with tiles, as opposed to 'icons'<br /><br />That said I dont particularly like them in my start menu; as I don't tend to have more than 20 items held within (I can search for anything else with just a few keystrokes, which essentially renders tiles obsolete IMO)<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=62">Jcee</a> — Thu Jun 16, 2016 8:12 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
</entry>
